Directions: Study the given information and answer the questions that follow.

Point A is 12 meters to the West of B. B is to the North of C. H is the midpoint of B and C. F is 9 meters to the West of E. E is 13 meters to the North of D. Distance Between C and D is 6 meters. E is in the North East direction of C. Distance between A and H is 13 meters. G is 8 meters South of F. G is in the West direction of H.

What is the distance between B and C?
8 meters
10 meters
12 meters
14 meters
None of these
Solution

1) Point A is 12 meters to the West of B.

2) B is to the North of C.

3) H is the midpoint of B and C.

4) E is 13 meters to the North of D.

5) E is in the North East direction of C.

6) Distance Between C and D is 6 meters.

7) F is 9 meters to the West of E.

      

8) Distance between A and H is 13 meters.

9) G is 8 meters South of F.

​10) G is in the West direction of H.

 

            

 As H is the Mid point of B and C so the distance between B and C is double of B and H.

 We know that the distance between B and H is

Applying Pythagoras Theorem

BH = \(\sqrt{\left(13^2-12^2\right)}\)= \(\sqrt{25}\)= 5 meters.

The distance between B and C is = (5 x 2) = 10 meters.

Four letter-clusters have been given, out of which three are alike in some manner and one is different. Select the letter-cluster that is different.
GVTB
XGCT
WDSH
DWJQ
Not Attempted
Solution

The pattern followed here is:

The logic followed here is:

Except option 1, sum of the place value of the letter of all the options is 54.

Option 1 → GVTB → 7 + 22 + 20 + 2 = 51

Option 2 → XGCT → 24 + 7 + 3 + 20 = 54

Option 3 → WDSH → 23 + 4 + 19 + 8 = 54

Option 4 → DWJQ → 4 + 23 + 10 + 17 = 54

Thus option 1 is odd one.

Hence, the correct answer is "Option 1".

C6F
8@U
28H
HK5
4YA
Solution

Hence, 4YA does not belong to the group.

General Intelligence & Reasoning
+1

Direction: Answer the questions based on the information given below:

Six persons M, N, O, P, Q and R are the top six rankers of the class. No two person got the same rank. The students who got the highest mark is given rank 1 and the student who got least mark is given rank 6. P got less mark than R and O. M got more marks than Q but less than P. N got the second least rank and R got the second highest rank. M got less mark than O.
Who among the following has rank 1?
O
R
P
M
Q
Solution

Six persons M, N, O, P, Q and R.

1) P got less mark than R and O.

R/O > P

2) M got more marks than Q but less than P.

P > M > Q

3) N got the second least rank and R got the second-highest rank.

O > R > P

4) M got less mark than O.

O > M

As N got the second least rank.

O > R > P > M > N > Q

The final arrangement is :

O > R > P > M > N > Q

Hence, O has highest rank.

Directions: Study the following information to answer the questions.

Ten persons are sitting in two parallel rows containing five-person each in such a way that there is an equal distance between adjacent persons. In row-1 P, Q, R, S, and T are seated and all of them are facing South. In row-2 A, B, C, D, and E are seated and all of them are facing North. Therefore, in the given seating arrangement each member seated in a row faces another member in the other row. S sits third to the right of Q where either of them is sitting on any of the extreme ends of the row. The one who faces Q sits second to the right of E. Two persons are sitting between B and E. Neither A nor C sits at an end of the row. The immediate neighbour of A faces the person who sits immediately to the right of Q. R and T are immediate neighbours of each other. T does not face the immediate neighbour of D.

What is the position of C with respect to A?
Second to the left
Immediate left
Immediate right
Third to the right
Second to the right
Solution

Facing South: P, Q, R, S, and T (Row – 1)

Facing North: A, B, C, D, and E (Row – 2)

1) S sits third to the right of Q where either of them is sitting on any of the extreme ends of the row

(Here, there are two possible cases, Case 1: Q sits at the extreme right end of the row, Case 2: S sits at the extreme left end of the row)

2) The one who faces Q sits second to the right of E.

3) Two persons are sitting between B and E.

(Here we can eliminate Case 1)
 

4) Neither A nor C sits at an extreme end of the row. 

(So D sits at the extreme end of row 2)

5) The immediate neighbour of A faces the person who sits immediately to the right of Q.

6) R and T are immediate neighbours of each other.

7) T does not face the immediate neighbour of D.

The final arrangement will be as follows.

Hence, C sits immediate left of A.

In row-1 P, Q, R, S, and T are seated and all of them are facing South. In row-2 A, B, C, D, and E are seated and all of them are facing North. Therefore, in the given seating arrangement each member seated in a row faces another member in the other row. S sits third to the right of Q where either of them is sitting on any of the extreme ends of the row. The one who faces Q sits second to the right of E. Two persons are sitting between B and E. Neither A nor C sits at an end of the row. The immediate neighbour of A faces the person who sits immediately to the right of Q. R and T are immediate neighbours of each other. T does not face the immediate neighbour of D.

Four of the following five are alike in a certain way and so form a group, find the one which does not belong to the group?
S
P
D
B
C
Solution

Facing South: P, Q, R, S, and T (Row – 1)

Facing North: A, B, C, D, and E (Row – 2)

1) S sits third to the right of Q where either of them is sitting on any of the extreme ends of the row

(Here, there are two possible cases, Case 1: Q sits at the extreme right end of the row, Case 2: S sits at the extreme left end of the row)

2) The one who faces Q sits second to the right of E.

3) Two persons are sitting between B and E.

(Here we can eliminate Case 1)
 

4) Neither A nor C sits at an extreme end of the row. 

(So D sits at the extreme end of row 2)

5) The immediate neighbour of A faces the person who sits immediately to the right of Q.

6) R and T are immediate neighbours of each other.

7) T does not face the immediate neighbour of D.

The final arrangement will be as follows.

S, P, D, and B are sitting at the extreme ends of the row. C sits in the middle of the row.

Hence, C does not belong to the group.

DIRECTIONS: In the following question assuming the given statements to be true, find which of the conclusion among the given conclusions is/are definitely true and then give your answers accordingly.

Conclusions :

I. S > P

II. U > R 

Only conclusion I follows
Only conclusion II follows
Both Conclusion I and II follow
Neither I  nor II follow
Either I or II follow
Solution

Given statements : P > Q < R, R = S ≥ T, T ≤  U > V

On combining : P > Q < R = S ≥ T ≤ U > V

(I) S > P → False (as S = R > Q < P there is no direct relation given between the two, it might be a possibility but not definitely true, Hence false )

(II) U > R → False (as U ≥ T ≤ S = R there is no direct relation given between the two, it might be a possibility but not definitely true, Hence false ).

Hence, Neither I nor  II follows.

Which Schedule of the Constitution provides for Anti-Defection Law?
10th
7th
3rd
1st
None of the above
Solution

The correct answer is 10th.Key Points

  • The Tenth Schedule - popularly known as the Anti-Defection Act - was included in the Constitution via the 52nd Amendment Act, of 1985.
  • It sets the provisions for disqualification of elected members on the grounds of defection to another political party.
  • The anti-defection law punishes individual Members of Parliament (MPs)/MLAs for leaving one party for another.
  • It allows a group of MP/MLAs to join (i.e., merge with) another political party without inviting the penalty for defection.
  • As per the 1985 Act, a 'defection' by one-third of the elected members of a political party was considered a 'merger'.
  • The 91st Constitutional Amendment Act, of 2003, changed this and now at least two-thirds of the members of a party must be in Favour of a "merger" for it to have validity in the eyes of the law.

Additional Information

Schedule Description
1st The first schedule contains the list of states and union territories and their territories
3rd The third Schedule contains the Forms of Oaths or Affirmations.
7th This schedule deals with the three legislative lists: Union, State, and Concurrent.

+1
El-Nino develops in which of these oceans?
Arctic Ocean
Indian Ocean
Atlantic Ocean
Pacific Ocean
Southern Ocean
Solution

The correct answer is Pacific Ocean.

Key Points:

EL- NINO:

  • El Nino (Spanish for Christ Child) is the occasional development of warm ocean surface waters along the coast of Ecuador and Peru in South America. 
  • Even though El Nino occurs in the Pacific Ocean, it often reduces the number of hurricanes that form in the Atlantic Ocean. Conversely, La Niña events tend to be related to an increase in the number of Atlantic hurricanes.
  • Recently this development has been used for forecasting climatic conditions in different parts of the world. 
  • The El Nino normally occurs around Christmas, roughly every 2 to 7 years, and lasts usually for a few weeks to a few months. 
  • El Nino event is related to two important atmospheric circulation systems:  
    • Hadley Circulation: It features air rising near the Equator, flowing poleward at a height of 10 to 15 kilometers above the earth’s surface, descending in the subtropics, and then returning equatorward near the surface. 
    • Walker Circulation: There is a stable low-pressure system above the western Pacific near South East Asia and a high-pressure system in the central Pacific.
  • This results in a constant westward flow of air masses from the area of high pressure to the area of low pressure. At higher altitudes, this air then flows directly eastward, oblique to the Hadley Circulation. 
  • Due to the combined components of Walker Circulation and Hadley Circulation, there is a strong prevailing wind toward the west in the lower layers of the atmosphere, which maintains the stable coastal upwelling system off the coast in western South America. 
  • El Nino and the Indian Monsoon rains are inversely related.

The Vernacular Press Act was repealed by __________.
Lord William Bentinck
Lord Lytton
Gladstone
Lord Ripon
None of these
Solution

Vernacular Press Act of 1878, proposed by Lytton the then Viceroy of India (1876-80)was also known as the Gagging Act and it was meant only for vernacular/ native language newspapers not for English ones.

  • According to this act, it was mandatory for the editors of Indian languages ​​newspapers to make a written assurance to the magistrate or collector of their respective areas that they would not publish such articles in their newspapers that spread resentment in public against the government or there is a possibility of spreading communal hatred.
  • Though the government was criticized in English-language newspapers also, Lytton did not consider these criticisms as objectionable. So on 14 March 1878, Lytton passed the Vernacular Press Act.

Important Points

Removal of restriction on Press:

  • Cranbrook, the Secretary of State was not in favour of the idea of the pre-censorship clause and later on it was done away with and a press commissioner was appointed to supply authentic and accurate news to the press.
  • The entire Vernacular Press Act of 1878 was repealed by Lord Ripon in 1882.

Thus, it is clear that the Vernacular Press Act was repealed by Lord Ripon.

Additional Information

  • Lord William Bentinck first came to India as governor of Madras in 1803 and was recalled in 1807 on account of the mutiny of the sepoys at Vellore in 1806.
    • After about two decades he was appointed the Governor-General of Bengal and took over the charge in 1828.

There are five scattered segments of a sentence given below, Identify the correct sequence of the segments to form the complete sentence and mark it as your answer.

A. crucial to the growth of 
B. innovation and creativity are 
C. of the 21st century 
D. becoming more and more 
E. the knowledge society 

DABEC
BDAEC
CABDE
BECDA
AECBD
Solution

The correct answer is option 2.

Key Points
  • Out of the given segments - 
  • Part B is the opening segment because it doesn't connect with any other given segments and thus, it is the introductory segment.
  • Part D and Part A are the second and third segments respectively because they are in continuation with part B and they talk about innovation and creativity becoming more and more crucial.
  • Part E is the fourth segment because it is in continuation with part A and it talks about innovation and creativity being more and more crucial for the growth of the knowledge society.
  • Part C is the fifth segment because it is in continuation with part E and it talks about innovation and creativity being more and more important for the growth of the knowledge society of the 21st century.
  • Hence, the correct sequence is BDAEC.

​

The complete sentence after rearrangement would be - Innovation and creativity are becoming more and more crucial to the growth of the knowledge society of the 21st century. 

Hint

  • How to solve sentence jumble?
  • Firstly, look for the segment which is independent and doesn't connect with any other segments or the option with has the subject matter. This will be the opening segment of the sentence.
  • Then, you need to look for connections between the given segments 
  • If there is a segment that is concluding the idea given in other segments that will be the ending segment.

+1

Directions: The following sentence has been split into five segments. Identify the segment that contains a grammatical error.

Neither students nor (A)/ their teacher are (B)/ participating in a wide (C)/ variety of activities, (D)/ both locally and further afield. (E)/.

A
B
C
D
E
Solution

The correct answer is 'B' i.e. this part of the sentence has an error.

Key Points

  • In the second part of the given sentence, the plural form of the verb 'are' is incorrect.
  • The subject of the given sentence is a compound subject ''Neither students nor their teacher''
  • When the compound subject is joined by or, nor, neither... nor, either... or and one part of the compound subject is singular and the other part is plural, the verb needs to agree with the part closest to it.
  • Therefore, the singular form of the verb 'is' should be used in place of the plural form of the verb 'are'.
     

Hence, the correct answer is option 2.

Correct sentence: Neither students nor their teacher is participating in a wide variety of activities, both locally and further afield.

Additional Information

  • Subjects and verbs must agree with one another in number (singular or plural).
  • Thus, if a subject is singular, its verb must also be singular; if the subject is plural, its verb must also be plural.

The question below contains five scattered segments of a sentence. Indicate the sequence which correctly assembles the segments and completes the sentence.

A. when Sweden defender

B. in the 98th minute

C. Marcus Danielson was sent off

D. the momentum shifted in extra time

E. for a red card

DCABE
DACBE
DACEB
ABDCE
None of the above
Solution

The correct answer is DACBE.

Key Points

  • Using the option elimination method we can find the opening sentence i.e. part D. Also D introduces the topic here, therefore, it will be the first part after rearrangement.
  • Part A introduces the person which is mentioned in the jumbled sentence. Hence A follows D.
  • Part C forms a complementary pair with part A as it mentions the name of the Swedish defender.
  • Part B refers to the time when the player was sent off, maintaining the logical flow of the sentence. Thus B follows C.
  • Part E becomes the concluding segment as it gives the reason why the player was sent off.


Correct rearrangement of segments is: The momentum shifted in extra time when Sweden defender Marcus Danielson was sent off in the 98th minute for a red card.

 

Complementary pair: It’s a pair formed by two segments/sentences in a para jumble where both the segments convey the same idea and are interdependent on each other.

The government has announced a decrease __________ the price of petrol and diesel.

under
in
of 
to
on

The correct answer is "in"

  • Similarly, the sentence in the question describes a change in the price of petrol and diesel, indicating that there has been a decrease.

The Ratio of length and breadth of the rectangle is 6 : 5. The perimeter of the rectangle is 440 cm. Find the area (cm2)of the rectangle.

18000
12000
9000
8000
15000
Solution

Given:

The perimeter of the rectangle = 440 cm

Formula Used:

Perimeter of the rectangle = 2 × (l + b)

Area of rectangle = length × breadth

Calculation:

Let the ratio be x

Length of the rectangle = 6x

Breadth of the rectangle = 5x

According to the question,

⇒ 440 = 2 × (6x +5x)

⇒ 220 = 11x

⇒ x = 20

So length of the rectangle = 6 × 20 = 120 cm

Breadth of the rectangle = 5 × 20= 100 cm

Area of the rectangle = length × breadth

⇒ Area = 120 × 100 = 12000 cm2

∴ Area of the rectangle = 12000 cm2

Quantitative Aptitude
+1
The total surface area of a cuboid is 1550 cm2. If the ratio of its length, breadth and height is 2 ∶ 3 ∶ 5, then find the volume of the cuboid.
3750 cm3
2775 cm3
3550 cm3
3000 cm3
4000 cm3
Solution

Given:

The total surface area of the cuboid = 1550 cm2 

The ratio of its length, breadth and height is 2 ∶ 3 ∶ 5

Formula Used:

The total surface area of the cuboid = 2(lb + bh + lh)

The volume of the cuboid = lbh

Where, l = Length of the cuboid

b = Breadth of the cuboid

h = Height of the cuboid

Calculation:

Let length(l), breadth(b) and height(h) of the cuboid be 2x, 3x and 5x respectively.

According to the question,

2(lb + bh + lh) = 1550

⇒ 2(2x × 3x + 3x × 5x + 5x × 2x) = 1550

⇒ 2(6x2 + 15x2 + 10x2) = 1550

⇒ 2 × 31x2 = 1550

⇒ x2 = 1550/62

⇒ x2 = 25

⇒ x = 5

Hence, l = 2x

⇒ 10 cm

b = 3x

⇒ 15 cm

h = 5x

⇒ 25 cm

The volume of the cuboid = lbh

⇒ 10 × 15 × 25

⇒ 3750 cm3

∴ The volume of the cuboid will be 3750 cm3.


Additional Information

Cuboid (घनभ)

Three-dimensional shape with length, breadth, and height

Each of the faces meets the other four faces.

The edges opposite to each other are parallel. 

Height = h, Length = l and Breadth = b

Points to Remember

For a cuboid,

Volume = l × b × h

Volume = Area of base × height

Surface area = 2(lb + bh + hl)

Diagonal = \(\sqrt {{l^2} + {b^2} + {h^2}} \)

Area of four walls = Perimeter of base × height = 2(l + b) × h

Volume of metal = External volume - internal volume

A question is given followed by information in three statements. You have to find out the data in which statement(s) is sufficient to answer the question and mark your answer accordingly.

The speed of the stream is 3 km/hr. Find the speed of the boat in still water.

I) The boat covered 20 km in 5 hours upstream.

II) The boat covered 20 km in 2 hours downstream.

Only II is sufficient
Either I or II is sufficient 
Both I & II are sufficient
None is sufficient
None of the above/More than one of the above
Solution

Let x km/h be the speed of the boat in still water

y = 3 km/hr

From Statement I:

Upstream speed of boat = x - y

⇒ x - y = 20/5

⇒ x - y = 4

⇒ x - 3 = 4

⇒ x = 7 km/h

From statement II:

Downstream speed of boat = x + y

⇒ x + y = 20/2

⇒ x + y = 10

⇒ x + 3 = 10

⇒ x = 7 km/h

Speed of boat in still water 7 km/hr

∴ Either I or II is sufficient.

The average of 5 numbers is 28. If the average of first three numbers is 18 then, find the average of remaining numbers?
45
46
42
49
43
Solution

Given:

Average of 5 numbers = 28

Average of first three numbers = 18

Concept used:

Average = (sum of all terms)/total number of terms

Sum of all terms = Average × total number of terms

Calculation:

Sum of 5 numbers = 5 × 28 = 140

Sum of first 3 numbers = 3 × 18 = 54

Sum of remaining numbers = 140 – 54 = 86

Number of remaining numbers = 2

Average of remaining numbers = 86/2 = 43

∴ The average of remaining numbers is 43

Ratio of Cost price to selling price of a book is 5 : 6 and ratio of selling price to marked price is 4 : 5. Marked price of the book is by what percent more than that of cost price of the book?
30%
50%
60%
40%
33%
Solution

Given

Ratio of Cost price to selling price of a book is 5 : 6 and ratio of selling price to marked price is 4 : 5

Formula:

x is what percent of y = (x/y) × 100

Calculation:

CP : SP = 5 : 6     --- (1) × 2

SP : MP = 4 : 5     --- (2) × 3

CP  : SP : MP = 10 : 12 : 15 = 10x : 12x : 15x

MP is more than CP by = 15x – 10x = 5x

∴ MP is more than CP by = (5x/10x) × 100 = 50%

148
Quantitative Aptitude
+1
The ratio of number of men and women in a ice-cream factory of 840 workers is 5 : 7. How many more men should be joined to make the ratio 1 : 1? 
240
200
190
140
160
Solution

Shortcut Trick

Men : Women = 5 : 7

Total number of workers = 840

⇒ The value of 12 → 840

⇒ The value of 1 → 70

Since more men are joining. But the women are the same. 

⇒ The value of 2 → 70 × 2 = 140

Hence, 140 more men should be joined to make the ratio 1 : 1.

Alternate Method

Let the men and women in the ice-cream factory be 5x and 7x respectively.

⇒ 5x + 7x = 840

⇒ 12x = 840

⇒ x = 70

Thus, Men = 5x = 5 × 70 = 350

And women = 7x = 7 × 70 = 490

Let y more men should be joined to make the ratio 1 : 1.

\(⇒ \frac{350 + y}{490}=\frac{1}{1}\)
⇒ 350 + y = 490

⇒ y = 140

Hence, 140 more men should be joined to make the ratio 1 : 1.

149
Quantitative Aptitude
+1
A boat can travel with a speed of 16 km/hr in still water. If the speed of the stream is 5 km/hr, find the time taken by the boat to go 63 km downstream.
2 hours
3 hours
4 hours
5 hours
None of these
Solution

Given:

Speed of boat in still water = 16 km/hr

Speed of the stream = 5 km/hr

Boat to go 63 km downstream

Formula used:

Time = distance/speed

If the speed of a boat in still water is u km/hr and the speed of the stream is v km/hr, then,

Speed downstream = (u + v) km/hr

Calculation:

Speed downstream = (16 + 5) km/hr = 21 km/hr

Time taken to travel 63 km downstream = (63/21) hrs = 3 hrs

∴ Time taken to travel 63 km downstream is 3 hrs.

Quantitative Aptitude
+1
A can do 50% more work than B in same time. B alone can do a piece of work in 30 hours. B starts working and had already worked for 12 hours when A joins him. How many hours should B and A work together to complete the remaining work?
16 hours
12 hours
4.8 hours
7.2 hours
9 hours
Solution

B alone can do the work in 30 hours and A can do 50% more work than B in same time;

∴ Time taken by A to complete the work alone = 30/1.5 = 20 hours

Suppose total work = 60 units (LCM of 20 & 30)

∴ Efficiency of A = 60/20 = 3 and,

Efficiency of B = 60/30 = 2;

Unit of work done by B in 12 hours = 12 × 2 = 24 units

∴ Remaining work = 60 - 24 = 36 units

∴ Time taken by (A + B) to complete the remaining work = 36/5 = 7.2 hours
